The error you're seeing:

pgsql
ImportError: cannot import name 'Flask' from partially initialized module 'app' 
(most likely due to a circular import)

✅ Cause:

This error usually happens because your Python file is named app.py, which conflicts with the Flask internal module name (app) and leads to circular imports.

✅ Solution:

Step 1: Rename your file

Rename your file from app.py to something else, like:

  • main.py

  • my_flask_app.py

  • ml_project.py

Step 2: Delete app.pyc and __pycache__ (if exists)

After renaming the file, also delete any cached Python files:

  • Delete app.pyc (if it exists)

  • Delete the __pycache__ folder

Step 3: Update the run command (if needed)

If you use the terminal to run the Flask app, do it like this (after renaming the file):

bash
set FLASK_APP=my_flask_app.py  # Windows CMD
$env:FLASK_APP = "my_flask_app.py"  # PowerShell

Then run:

bash
flask run

    app.run(debug=True)

✅ Step 1: Create static/ Folder

Inside your project folder, create:

  • static/style.css → for your CSS

✅ Step 2: Create or Update templates/index.html

Here's a sample index.html using a CSS file and an image:

html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8" />
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0" />
    <title>My Flask Page</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="{{ url_for('static', filename='style.css') }}">
</head>
<body>
    <div class="hero">
        <h1>Welcome to Flask!</h1>
        <p>This is a sample Flask page using HTML + CSS</p>
        <img src="{{ url_for('static', filename='images/wine.png') }}" alt="Wine Image" />
    </div>
</body>
</html>

{{ url_for('static', filename='...') }} is Flask’s way to load static files safely.

✅ Step 3: Sample static/style.css

Create a file: static/style.css
Paste:

css

    padding: 30px;
}

python
from flask import Flask, render_template

app = Flask(__name__)

@app.route('/')
def home():
    return render_template('index.html')  # Uses home.css

@app.route('/about')
def about():
    return render_template('about.html')  # Uses about.css

if __name__ == '__main__':
    app.run(debug=True)

🔷 2. templates/index.html

html

    <title>Home Page</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="{{ url_for('static', filename='home.css') }}">
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Welcome to Home Page</h1>
    <p>This is the main page.</p>
    <a href="{{ url_for('about') }}">Go to About</a>
</body>
</html>

🔷 3. templates/about.html

html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>

    <title>About Page</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="{{ url_for('static', filename='about.css') }}">

<body>
    <h1>About Us</h1>
    <p>This is the about page.</p>

You're almost there! Your HTML looks great, but the video and image files are not showing because they’re not being loaded correctly in Flask.

Let me explain and fix it for you:

🧠 Why it's not working:

  1. Flask does not serve media files (videos, images, CSS, JS) unless they are placed inside the static/ folder.

  2. Direct paths like src="wine.jpg" won't work — Flask won't find them unless you use url_for('static', ...).

✅ Fix Folder Structure First

Move your media files like this:

css
ML PROJECT/
├── main.py
├── templates/
│   └── index.html
├── static/
│   ├── style.css
│   ├── wine video.mp4
│   ├── red wine.jpg
│   ├── wine.jpg
│   └── wine glass.avif

✅ Update HTML to use Flask's url_for for each media file:

🔧 Update video:

html
<video autoplay muted loop>
  <source src="{{ url_for('static', filename='wine video.mp4') }}" type="video/mp4" />
</video>

🔧 Update image paths:

html
<div class="image-grid">
  <img src="{{ url_for('static', filename='red wine.jpg') }}" alt="Red Wine" />
  <img src="{{ url_for('static', filename='wine.jpg') }}" alt="Wine Bottles" />
  <img src="{{ url_for('static', filename='wine glass.avif') }}" alt="Wine Glass" />

✅ Final Tips:

  • Do not use spaces in file names if possible (e.g., rename wine video.mp4 to wine_video.mp4) — spaces sometimes cause path issues.

  • After renaming, update the HTML accordingly:
